        "title": "The Half That Was Missing Was Me",
        "content": "# CHAPTER 27\n## The Half That Was Missing Was Me\n\nThe final exhibition.\n\"Rebirth\".\n\nThe gallery was full.\nCamila was in the center, wearing a red dress (a color she hadn't worn for years because Ricardo said it was \"too flashy\").\nShe was flashy. She was bright.\n\nHer paintings told the story on the wall.\nThe woman sinking. The woman emerging. The woman flying.\n\nMaria, the journalist, asked:\n\"Camila, what is the main message of this series?\"\n\nCamila looked at the paintings. Looked at the hall.\nSaw her mother, with pink hair, laughing with Fernanda.\nSaw Leo and Bia running, healthy, loved.\nSaw Daniel, talking to someone, but casting a look of pride at her from across the room.\n\nShe took a deep breath.\n\n\"The message is about wholeness,\" answered Camila. \"We grow up hearing that we need to find the 'other half of the orange'. That we are incomplete until we find a partner.\"\n\nShe paused. The hall fell silent to listen.\n\n\"I spent years looking for this half. I tried to fit into other people's halves. I cut myself, diminished myself, silenced myself to fit.\"\n\"But the secret... the great secret no one tells... is that we are already born whole.\"\n\nCamila smiled. A smile that lit up the place.\n\n\"The divorce wasn't about losing a husband. It was about finding myself.\"\n\"The half that I was missing wasn't a man. It wasn't a status.\"\n\"The half that was missing... was me.\"\n\nApplause.\nNot polite. Emotional.\nWomen in the audience with teary eyes. Fernanda whistling.\n\nCamila looked at Daniel. He winked. He knew. He didn't want to be her half. He wanted to be a whole walking beside another whole.\n\nLater, when the lights went out and the gallery emptied, Camila stayed one last moment alone with her paintings.\n\nShe touched the canvas of the painting \"Flight\".\nThe dry paint under her fingers.\n\n\"We did it,\" she whispered.\n\nWent out into the starry night of São Paulo.\nThe air was cold, but she didn't feel it.\nShe had the fire inside her now.\nAnd this fire would never, never go out.\n\n**THE END**\n"
